Midterm assignment-predicting house price

Xiaoyi Wu, Yebei Yao

10/20/2021

01. Introduction & Motivation

1.1 Brief introduction of Boulder County and the analysis background.

As the most-visited real estate website in the United States, Zillow and its affiliates offer customers an on-demand experience for selling, buying, renting and financing with transparency and nearly seamless end-to-end service. These years,Zillow have produced home value reports for the nation and over 130 metropolitan statistical areas. The reports identify market trends including, but not limited to: five and 10-year annualized change, negative equity, short sales and foreclosure transactions.

Hypothetically, in this project, Zillow has realized that its housing market predictions are not as accurate as they could be,because they do not factor in enough local intelligence. As such they have held a competition and asked our team to build a better predictive model of home prices for Boulder County, CO.

Real estate market is growing in Colorado year-over-year. Located in north-central Colorado, northwest of Denver, the county’s landscape includes several dense urban centers surrounded by rural buffer zones and mountain communities, plus portions of Rocky Mountain National Park.The namesake boulders are remnants from the last ice age, but some originated in the Rocky Mountains to the west. Bounder is quirky and weird, something that made it the perfect setting for the TV show “Mork and Mindy”.

Here are several main characteristic of Boulder county house market: Close lacation with Denver:The Boulder real estate market has all the earmarks of being sustainable. It has benefited a lot from its close proximity to Denver. The unemployment rate of Boulder city is well below the national average and with a strong economy to back it up, it will further drop in the coming years.

abundant landscape features from farmland and rolling grasslands in the plainsSnug against the foothills where the Great Plains give rise to the Rocky Mountains, Boulder is nothing if not a looker. This city reveals its spectacle at the crest of a hill on U.S. Route 36 from Denver with its iconic sandstone slabs rising from the mountains, prefaced by pine-clad mesas and cradled within the backdrop of the snow-capped Indian Peaks. There are around 200 miles of hiking trails and massive amounts of green space.

Livable metro areasIn the metro area, there are roughly 300,000 people.The destrict has seen growth as people move from the expensive, over-crowded Denver area to a city where you can still hike in the mountains and see the hills.Considering the satisfication residents are with their daily lives by metro area, and takes into account factors like crime, quality and availability of health care, quality of education and average commute time.It ranks second in Best Places to live for quality of life in U.S. News.

In the project, we adopted geospatial machine learning techniques, split the existing housing sale price data sets into training and test set, incorporated local intelligence features from Census data, public services and natural resources, also both Boulder county and Boulder city Open Data portal, as well as Open Street Map data, combined all those features and trained the final model,in order to achieve the lowest possible error rate. As result, our team has the Mean Absolute Errors(MAE) and the Mean Absolute Percent Errors (MAPE) is 194219.5 and 0.3088744 respectively.

02.Data Manipulation and Visualization

2.1 Summary of the data sets needed in the whole process.

The data used in the model are mainly dependent variable and independent variables,in this case, the dependent variable is house price of Boulder county nested in the data set from Zillow.The independent variables are selected factors which may be the influencing factors to the house price. With the independent variables, we’d like to predict some of the unknown house price.
In general,there are five kinds of data sets we use in the whole process:

  • 01.Boulder House Price and Internal Characteristics of the House Price: the basic geometric data provided by the professor, where the internal characteristics are concluded. Several research on the determined factors related to Boulder County house price will be helpful when we try to make choice to extract internal from the data set.
    The internal/parcel characteristic we choose are presented as follow:
  1. qualityCode: Description of the quality as determined by our appraisal staff – see qualityCode. 
  2. builtYear: Year in which the building began construction.
  3. EffectiveYear: The effective year built.
  4. bsmtSF: Square footage of the basement type.
  5. carStorageSF: Square footage of the car storage.
  6. nbrBedRoom: Number of bedrooms.
  7. nbrRoomsNobath: Total number of rooms excluding bathrooms (non-mobile residential only).
  8. mainfloorSF: Total finished square footage of the main floor (non-commercial only).
  9. nbrThreeQtrBaths: Number of ¾ bathrooms ( shower, no bathtub) for non-mobile residential only.
    10.nbrFullBaths: Number of full bathrooms (contains a bathtub) for non-mobile residential only.
    11.bathnum:number of bathroom, new column created with existed column.

  • 02.Boulder Base Data: Base geometric map, in other words, the boundary of Boulder county.

  • 03.census tract and some neighborhood units of Boulder County:As an alternative way to using neighborhood data of the whole Boulder County, we used the geometric data from census tract of Boulder county in 2019.

  • 04.Census Data:demographic variables from the ACS2019. After doing some research get some basic understanding Boulder county, we specifically selected eleven variables for further analysis.We specifically selected 12 variables and created features and applied them in our model. 12 variables: + TotalPop:Total population in each census tract +Whites:White population in each census tract +MedHHInc:Median household income in each census tract +MedRent：Median Rent for properties in each census tract +TotalPoverty：Population living under the level of poverty in each census tract +TotalVacant:Total vacant unit in each census tract +ForRent :houses for rent in each census tract. +ForRentVac: houses for rent but in vacancy in each census tract. +ForSale: houses for sale in each census tract. +ForSaleVac: houses for sale and in vacant in each census tract. +TotalUnit :Total housing units in each census tract +RenterOccupied:Total householder lived in renter-occupied housing units 5 features +pctWhite: the percentage of white people in each census tract. +pctPoverty :the percentage of household in poverty. +pctTotalVacant:the percentage of house in vacant condition. +TotalOccupied: the number of occupied houses. +pctRenterOccupied: the percentage of households living in renter-occupied housing units in each census tract

  • 05.Public services Amenity data:We collected several compilatory data from Boulder opendata and other complementary datasets(like open street map),with those datasets, we will be able to describe the amenity and public service exposure of Boulder county.
    The datasets we use embrace the health care service, entertainment accessibility, natural resources, open space, education opportunity and so on. Each datasets are presented as follow: +01.CDPHE Health Facilities:Addresses represented as point locations for regulated CDPHE health facilities,from CDPHE Health Facilities and Emergency Medical Services Division. +02.Transit system: in both linear and point form,which are area trails and traffic stations. +03.open space: open spaces in the county. +04.libraries:public libraries in the county. +05.Landmark: Landmarks in the county. +06.school: point school data from open street map. +07.restaurant: point restaurant data from open street map. +08.theater: point theater data from open street map.

  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001E, 
         Whites = B02001_002E,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001E, 
         MedRent = B25058_001E,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002E,
         TotalVacant = B25002_003E,
         ForRent = B25004_002E,
         ForRentVac = B25004_003E,
         ForSale = B25004_004E,
         ForSaleVac = B25004_005E,
         TotalUnit = B25001_001E,
         RenterOccupied = B08137_003E
         ) %>%
  dplyr::select(-NAME, -starts_with("B")) %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop,0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         pctTotalVacant = ifelse(TotalUnit > 0, TotalVacant / TotalUnit * 100, 0),
         TotalOccupied = TotalUnit - TotalVacant,
        pctRenterOccupied = ifelse(TotalOccupied >0, RenterOccupied/TotalOccupied, 0)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites, -TotalPoverty)

2.2.5 Feature engineering.

Feature engineering is the process of transforming raw data into features that better represent the underlying problem to the predictive models, which will be helpful to improve the accuracy on our prediction.

In this case,When considering the effect of amenity features to the house price, we have to measure the accessibility,in other words, the exposure the houses locations to the amenities locations.

Since the amenities,like landmarks,transit stations,health care centers, are data sets in the form of geometry, we have to create new features measurable. In spatial background, it’s easy to consider distance as the metrics.In order to lower the impact of bias in measurement, or arbitrary areal unit setting, or fixed buffer distance of each home sale observation,we decide to calculate the ‘average nearest neighbor distance’ from each home sale to its k nearest neighbor crimes. Take the spreading density of the amenities into consideration, we set k equeals three to five.

st_c <- st_coordinates

      health_nn1 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 1),

After all the potential related features are set,we have to make several exploratory analysis so as to decide which features can better predict the houseprice. *Correlation matrix, in this process,we calculate bivariate correlation and statistical significance, respectively. After drawing all the features,we make detailed correlation matrix for different types of features. In the following figures 2.4.1 to 2.4.4,blue indicates positive correlation between two features, while green indicates negative correlations.And the dark the color is, the stronger correlationship is.

*correlation scatterplots:with the scatterplots, we can illustrate price as a function of continuous variables, and visualize the direct relationship between house price and the potential features.

03. Methods

This project adopted geospatial machine learning techniques, split housing the sale price data Our goal is to train the machine to predict house price with the existing data as accurate and generalized as possible. We firstly have to build a ordinary least squres regression model with several features,the try to adjust selected features to optimization model. But how could we know which model fit better?Then here comes the test work. With the provided datasets, we randomly split them into training and test datasets. Models will be trained on the former and tested on the latter. The training data occupies 75% of the all observations while testing data is 25%.
In this multivariate case, the dependent variable is house price, while the independent variables are features we discussed above in section two. Based on the hedonic home price model, potential features encompass three components:internal features,neighborhood amenities/public services and the underlying spatial process of prices.
After data wrangling and feature engineering work and correlation exploration, we finally got 59 features.We gradually narrow the range and finally got the features which altogether best predict the house price.
The work flow of select the best fit features which give us the model with more accuracy and generalizability.We map,plot,make comparison with the following parameters of the model.
MAE: Mean Absolute Error (MAE):calculated by taking the mean of the absolute values of subtracting each predicted housing prices from the corresponding given prices in the testing dataset.
MAPE: Mean Absolute Percent Error (MAPE):the mean of Absolute Percent Error of each validation pairs - the difference between predicted and observed prices on a percentage basis.
R-squared:in this case,it means that how much difference the features in regression model has made to make the prediction closer to the real house price.
MSE: Mean Squared Error ,the averaged deviation from the correct values for the whole dataset.
RMSE: Root Mean Squared Error,the square root of MSE, which is a measure the distribution of the residual.
After consider the parameters, we can get the final model. Then we use k-fold cross validation to see whether the model is generalized or not, whether the residual are spatial correlated or not.

4.4 cross-validation tests

we conduct cross-validation test to assess the generalization of the final model. We split the training set into k smaller sets, in this case,100 folders, using 99 of the folds as training data,the resulting model is validated on the remaining part of the data. Within the Cross-validation Test Summary table, the R-square, RMSE, and MAE in each of 100 fold are presented.Then we present first five output for better readability. In order to better visualize those 100 results, we made histograms and scatter plot,however, the result indicates errors are clustering tightly together,meaning that he models’ ability in predicting prices is not very satisfying. One guess to the results might be the complemental data is not enough for picturing the determined factors to house price in Boulder.

4.6 provide a map of test set’s residuals

In order to examine if the prediction have spatial autocorrelation problem,that is, if prediction errors display certain spatial patterns, clustered spatially. We used three tools help us to know about it.The model with less spatial autocorrelation is more generalized one. We use three method testing it. map of residuals: When map the residuals around the boulder. spatial lags plot: A spatial lag is a variable that averages the. neighboring values of a location. we made a scatter plot of residuals. moran’s I:Moran’s I is a correlation coefficient that measures the overall spatial autocorrelation of the data.

4.6.1The first one is to map the residuals gained through the model.

Through the map we can see that the residuals tend to cluster in urban districts,but it’s kind of hard to read through the plotted map.

map_residual<- ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data=boulder.boundary)+
  geom_sf(data=model_test2,
          aes(color=q5(SalePrice.Error)),
          show.legend = "point",size = 1)+  
                    scale_color_manual(values =  c(palette),
                     labels = qBr(model_test2,'SalePrice.Error'),
                     name = "Residuals") +
  labs(title = 'Map of residuals on test set\n') +
  mapTheme() + 
  plotTheme()
map_residual

4.6.2The second way of showing spatial cluster extend is plotting spatial lags.

Spatial lag is a variable that averages the neighboring values of a location.In this case, we use census tract units as the neighborhood.The flowing figure plots SalePrice as a function of spatial lag.The interpretation of this plot is that as price increases, so does the price of nearby houses.

## Spatial lag in errors: average errors in five nearest neighbors
k_nearest_neighbors = 5
# average errors in five nearest neighbors
coords.test <- st_centroid(st_geometry(model_test2),
                           of_largest_polygon=TRUE)

neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, k_nearest_neighbors))

spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W") 


model_test2$lagPriceError <- lag.listw(spatialWeights.test,model_test2$SalePrice.Error)

error.spatial.lag <- ggplot(model_test2, 
                            aes(x = lagPriceError, y = SalePrice.Error)) +
  geom_point(colour = "black") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "darkred") +
  labs(title = "Error on Test Set as a function of the Spatial Lag of Price\n",
       x = "Spatial lag of errors (Mean error of 5 nearest neighbors)",
       y = "Errors of Sale Price") +
  plotTheme()

error.spatial.lag

4.6.3The third way of measuring spatial autocorrelation is Moran’s I.

In our model, the Moran’s I is 0.2397,which means the model error is clustered in certain level but not very high,in other words, to some extend, there is spatial autocorrelation. To assess the significance of the Moran’s I statistic against a null hypothesis of no spatial autocorrelation, we randomly permuted Moran’s I and plotted them as a histogram with the Observations. The orange lines shows that the observed Moran’s I is higher and locates far away the central of the histogram, also，the pseudo p-value is 0.001, which indicates that we can reject the null hypothesis that the the house price is randomly distributed that is there really is spatial autocorrelation in house price.

moranTest <- moran.mc(model_test2$SalePrice.AbsError, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

moran.plot <- ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), 
                     aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "orange",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in orange, I = 0.2383",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count") +
  plotTheme()
moran.plot

4.10.1 Context Group Building

we selected four census variables to display the spatial pattern of each group:
1)majority white vs. majority non-white:divided whether the proportion of white population is accounted for more than 50% of total population or not. high income vs. low income:divided by whether the income is higher than the mean of medium household income or not.
2)majority vacant vs.majority non-vacant:whether the proportion of vacant unit is accounted for more than half of total vacant unit or not.
3)majority renter occupied vs majority non-renter occupied:divided whether the proportion of renter occupied units is accounted for more than 50% of total units or not.
4)According to the presented maps,we find out the vacancy,income and renter occupitaion displayed the obvious spatial pattern, we determined to generalize our model on the two context groups.

4.10.3 Generalizability on Context Groups

Despite the higher MAPE for neighborhood model, and all the way high MAPEin the final model, baseline model and neighborhood model, the Majority Non-White group, the baseline model is generalized well across context groups with MAPE close to the one generated on the test set (MAPE on test set is 30.88% for your reference).

05. Discussion

  • Accuracy and Generalizability: Although we made many model and adjusted the selected features, the MAPE doesn’t change much all the way, which lead to lower accuracy and generalizability. We analysis the cause might be amenity data we loaded in and census data we chose from are not very related to the house price.We hope with more corresponding data, the predicting process could give us a better result. When testify the generalizability, when we took neighborhood into consideration, although MAPE change higher,but doesn’t make much difference. The underlying reason might because we didn’t take those natural resource and landscape properties like beautiful vision into consideration.Those features are the characteristic of Boulder,which might be more important and related tightly with the house price. And there is a weird thing when we trying to figure out the distribute pattern of race, aka the white people, but when we extract census data and calculate the percentage of white people with the data of total population, in some neighborhood, the percentage of white people is even higher than the total people! We assume this might because of the limitation of original dataset.
  • Errors and Spatial Variations: In order to capture spatial autocorrelation,we use both spatial lag and moran’s I to see the cluster

In this way, the model captures the spatial autocorrelation very well. We included this predictor in the model in the end and it significantly increases the model prediction.

Considering the spatial pattern,some of those features are not linear, so we can not simply explain them in OLS regression, we think the relatively poor performance may be because of it.

06. Conclusion

Although our model has relatively higher MAPE, the data we loaded are quite comprehended, and the model we adjusted the feature we used in several model, the final model is the best one we got. We would like to reccomand our model to Zillow. However, we think maybe thecolinearity between various features is hard to clear, which affect our final result, also because some of the houses locates in the urban district, but the natural sources especially landmarks and trails are located in the mountain, this could explain our inaccuracy to the model. Additionally, when using regression model, maybe we use log transformed for some of those feature can be helpful, but there are too many features and the difficulties transforming stoped us. We believe in the future, by optimizing the model, the results will turn better.
